passages.text: Bottoming out, maintain

We think 1H25 marks the tough of profitability. Zhongsheng (ZS)'s 1H25 earnings were \(\sim 20\%\) shy of JPMc, dragged by record low margins in new car sales as a result of 1) fierce price competition in auto market and 2) limited rebate from OEMs, which we expect to increase meaningfully in 2H25. We notice industry- wide price discounts hit record highs by June - right before the Chinese government intervened and launched its anti- involution campaign to curb irrational pricing behavior among OEMs. We upgraded ZS to OW on July 28 (here) on long- term expectations that ZS will see structural profitability improvement from anti- involution efforts in the next 1- 2 years. This view remains intact.

Recap of our LT thesis and mgmt comments on the result call: 1) Initiatives from Benz and BMW: At JPMorgan's recent global auto forum in London (here), we learnt and were encouraged by Benz and BMW's targets to restructure their dealer networks by closing \(\sim 15 - 20\%\) of poor quality stores in China in the next year. This should benefit leading players including ZS. Our channel checks suggest Benz and BMW have closed \(\sim 4\%\) of their stores in China in recent months. 2) Benz, which accounted for \(35\%\) of ZS' new car sales revenue in H25, is entering into a powerful product cycle in 2026- 27 with 31 new or facelifted models across the BEV and ICE portfolio. We hence expect narrowing price discounts for Benz (currently c. \(15 - 20\%\) ) and potentially other premium brands in the next two years; 3) Overseas expansion for selected mainland Chinese brands likely starting in Hong Kong, Macau or neighboring markets given much higher GPM (generally \(8 - 10\%\) ) in overseas markets vs. domestic \((- 2 - 4\%)\) ; we would welcome this move if it materializes. 4) Anticipated further rebate from OEMs in 2H25: OEMs' rebate or compensation collectively translated into \(>Rmb15k\) per car in 2024 but was fairly limited in 1H25, hence we believe OEMs will offer rebates to quality dealers such as ZS in 2H25 rather than to smaller dealers that may be subject to closure.

1H25 result highlights: 1) New car sales fell by \(5\%\) you due to \(2\%\) yoy volume declining and \(5\%\) ASP contraction. GPM contracted to \(- 4.1\%\) due to fierce price- competition and narrowing OEM rebate in 1H25. We expect OEM rebates to increase meaningfully in 2H25, driving an improved GPM in 2H25. Aftermarket business: revenue was sustained with GPM remaining solid at \(47.4\%\) . 3) Opex ratio widened slightly by 0.1ppt to \(5.9\%\) in 1H25. Overall, net profit slipped by \(36\%\) yoy, in part due to higher base last year.

Earnings revisions and investor feedback on our recent upgrade: We trim ZS' 2025/26 estimates by \(\sim 16\% /12\%\) to reflect the 1H25 run rate. Our LT positive stance remains unchanged. Investor feedback towards our recent upgrade has been generally positive; the main "pushback" is most investors think noticeable profitability improvement will not be seen until 4Q25/ 1Q26 or beyond - this is also our base case.
Sources for: Style Exposure - J.P. Morgan Global Markets Strategy; all other tables are company data and J.P. Morgan estimates.

We have an OW rating on Zhongsheng Auto as: (1) Benz's streamlining of its dealer network will help leading players such as Zhongsheng; (2) Benz is entering into a powerful model cycle in China (as well as globally) with \(\sim 30\) new and facelifted models across BEV and ICE offerings, and across AGM and Benz brands in 2026 and 2027; and (3) a generally improving pricing trend in China (as a result of the government's anti- involution campaign) should help to support dealers' margins.

Our June- 26 PT of HK\$20 is based on DCF, as a PE multiple may not accurately reflect ZSG's earnings recovery, while DCF reflects LT normalized earnings and cash flow. We assume a WACC of \(11\%\) and \(3\%\) terminal growth. Our PT implies 13x FY26 PE, which is still below ZSG's historical average 14x which we believe is reasonable.

We have an OW rating on Zhongsheng Auto as: (1) Benz's streamlining of its dealer network will help leading players such as Zhongsheng; (2) Benz is entering into a powerful model cycle in China (as well as globally) with \(\sim 30\) new and facelifted models across BEV and ICE offerings, and across AGM and Benz brands in 2026 and 2027; and (3) a generally improving pricing trend in China (as a result of the government's anti- involution campaign) should help to support dealers' margins.

Our June- 26 PT of HK\$20 is based on DCF, as a PE multiple may not accurately reflect ZSG's earnings recovery, while DCF reflects LT normalized earnings and cash flow. We assume a WACC of \(11\%\) and \(3\%\) terminal growth. Our PT implies \(13x\) FY26 PE, which is still below ZSG's historical average \(14x\) which we believe is reasonable.
